{{Infobox Protected area | name = Chaco National Park | iucn_category = II | photo = Carpincho lake in National park Chaco.JPG | photo_caption = Carpincho lake in National park Chaco | map = Argentina | relief = 1 | map_caption = | map_width = 175 | location = [[Chaco Province]], [[Argentina]] | nearest_city = | coordinates = {{coords|26|50|S|59|40|W|region:AR|format=dms|display=inline, title}} | area_km2 = 150 | established = 1954 | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | governing_body = [[Administración de Parques Nacionales]] }}
The '''Chaco National Park''' ({{lang-es|Parque Nacional Chaco}}) is a [[national park]] of [[Argentina]], located in the [[provinces of Argentina|province]] of [[Chaco Province|Chaco]]. It has an area of 150&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>. It was created in 1954 in order to protect a sample of the Eastern Chaco, composed mainly of warm lowlands, with an annual summer rainfall between 750 and 1,300&nbsp;mm.
This park is a protected area for the [[quebracho tree]]s. Forests of ''quebracho colorado chaqueño'' (''[[Schinopsis balansae]]'') were once located in the north of [[Santa Fe Province|Santa Fe]] and the western half of Chaco, and had entered the northeast region of the province of [[Corrientes Province|Corrientes]]. Its strong wood and its abundant [[tannin]] caused it to be [[over-exploited]] for a century.
The area harbors several environments: [[scrubland]], [[savanna]], [[swamp]]s, and small lakes. The scrubland is the habitat of the red quebracho (''[[Schinopsis lorentzii]]''), white quebracho (''[[Aspidosperma quebracho-blanco]]''), algarrobo (''[[Prosopis alba]]''), and lapacho (''[[Tabebuia]]'' spp.), all of which are commercially valuable species. The fauna includes large predators such as [[cougar]]s. In the lakes one finds [[yacare caiman]]s and [[capybara]]s. Elsewhere there are [[armadillo]]s, [[South American tapir]]s and [[plains viscacha]]s, as well as birds (more than 340 species). The fauna also includes the black howler monkey (''[[black howler|Alouatta caraya]]'').
Indigenous communities of the [[Mocoví people|Mocoví]] and [[Toba (tribe)|Toba]] peoples are found in the protected area.
